# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alasdair-cochrane
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Since the launch of the site in 2008, the number of users has grown rapidly, reaching about 10 million daily visits in early 2022.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] By 2024, Academia.edu has over 270 million registered users, with over 55 million papers currently available on the platform.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In 2022, the company entered the scientific publishing sector, launching a dozen scientific, open access journals, and publishing under the name of Academia.edu Journals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Academia.edu was founded by Richard Price in 2008.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] On its filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company uses the legal name Academia Inc.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] The site was registered in the .edu top-level domain in 1999 when that domain was not limited to educational institutions.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In 2013, Elsevier sent thousands of takedown notices to Academia.edu, claiming copyright infringement for Elsevier-published content that was posted on Academia.edu.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Following widespread complaint of these takedown notices, Elsevier retracted their request, and academics were allowed to continue to post their publications.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Critics mention several alternatives for free access publications for people who want to make their work freely available.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Many universities and educational consortia have their own institutional repositories, including the Big Ten Academic Alliance.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Zenodo (funded by The OpenAIRE Consortium) and Humanities Commons both work to keep humanities scholarship online without monetizing it.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Academia.edu's competitors include ResearchGate, Google Scholar and Mendeley.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In 2016 Academia.edu reportedly had more registered users than ResearchGate (about 34 million versus 11 million) and higher web traffic, but ResearchGate had substantially more active usage by researchers.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In 2020, the traffic ranks had reversed, with ResearchGate ranked in the top 150–200 websites globally according to Alexa Internet, whereas Academia.edu was positioned in the 200–300 range.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Unpaywall, which collects data about open access versions of academic publications and provides easy access to them, is also considered a competitor to Academia.edu.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] As of December 2025, Academia.edu Journals has launched 18 open-access journals that publish articles in various scientific fields, including medicine.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] As a gold open-access publisher, all articles are freely available.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] All journals waived article processing charges for authors during the year in which the journal was launched, and continue to waive these fees for authors who come from eligible countries or can prove difficulty with paying due to lack of funding.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Academia.edu is not a university or institution for higher learning and so under current standards it would not qualify for the ".edu" top-level domain.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] However, since the domain name "Academia.edu" was registered in 1999, before the regulations required .edu domain names to be held solely by accredited post-secondary institutions in the US, it is allowed to remain active and operational.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] All .edu domain names registered before 2001 were grandfathered in, even if not an accredited USA post-secondary institution.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Academia.edu claims it supports the open science or open access movements and, in particular, instant distribution of research, and a peer-review system that occurs alongside distribution, instead of before it.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Accordingly, the company stated its opposition to the proposed (since withdrawn) 2011 U.S.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Research Works Act, which would have prevented open-access mandates in the U.S.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] However, in the view of critic Peter Suber, Academia.edu is not an open access repository and is not recommended as a way to pursue green open access.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Peter Suber instead invites researchers to use field-specific repositories or general-purpose repositories like Zenodo.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In early 2016, some users reported having received e-mails from Academia.edu where they were asked if they would be interested in paying a fee to have their papers recommended by the website's editors.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] This led some users to start a campaign encouraging users to cancel their Academia.edu accounts.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] Other criticisms include the fact that Academia.edu uses a vendor lock-in model: "It's up to Academia.edu to decide what you can and can't do with the information you've given them, and they're not likely to make it easy for alternative methods to access".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] This is in reference to the fact that, although papers can be read by non-users, a free account is needed in order to download papers: "you need to be logged in to do most of the useful things on the site (even as a casual reader)".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] In December 2016, Academia.edu announced new premium features that includes data analytics on work and the professional rank of the viewers, which have also received criticism.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/academia-edu] This strategy, where key financial terms are presented in visually muted text with low contrast, is viewed as a violation of transaction transparency principles and consumer protection standards.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's work forms part of the political turn in animal ethics—that is, the emergence of academic literature exploring the normative aspects of human/nonhuman animal relationships from a political perspective.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He is known for his interest-based account of animal rights, a theory of justice according to which animals have rights based on their possession of normatively-significant interests.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The account is a two-tiered one, with individuals' strong interests grounding *prima facie* rights, and some *prima facie* rights becoming concrete, or all-things-considered, rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In this picture, the violation of concrete rights, but not necessarily *prima facie* rights, represents an injustice.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In particular, Cochrane argues that sentient animals' interests against suffering and death ground *prima facie* rights against the infliction of suffering and death.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] These *prima facie* rights convert to concrete rights in, for example, animal agriculture and animal testing, meaning that killing nonhuman animals or making them suffer for these purposes is unjust.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane argues that nonhuman animals do not possess an intrinsic interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Therefore, owning or using nonhuman animals is not, in itself, unjust.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] This aspect of his thought has generated responses by others, including the political theorist Robert Garner and the philosopher John Hadley, who argue that there may be reasons to claim that nonhuman animals do possess an interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane has also proposed a cosmopolitan alternative to Sue Donaldson and Will Kymlicka's picture of a political animal rights, explicated in their 2011 book *Zoopolis*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Though Donaldson and Kymlicka have defended their account against Cochrane's criticism, they have said that they welcome attempts to develop alternative political theories of animal rights to their own.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's other research focusses variously on bioethics, punishment, just war and human rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Alasdair Cochrane studied in the Department of Politics at Sheffield as an undergraduate.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] There, he was taught by James Meadowcroft, a specialist in environmental politics, who sparked his interest in political and environmental philosophy.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] During a course on environmental politics, Cochrane read Joel Feinberg's "The Rights of Animals and Unborn Generations", which he recalled as probably the first piece of "pro-animal" scholarship he read.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The first piece of "pro-animal" scholarship he wrote was his undergraduate dissertation, in which he explored the possibility of a reconciliation between sustainable development and animal rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane received a first-class honours degree in politics in 2000 from the university.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He subsequently obtained an MSc in political theory from the London School of Economics (LSE).
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] It was during this time that he met Cécile Fabre, who went on to become his PhD supervisor.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2007, Cochrane received a PhD from the Department of Government at the LSE.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] His thesis, supervised by Fabre with Paul Kelly acting as an advisor, was entitled *Moral obligations to non-humans*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In that year, Cochrane published his first peer-reviewed research article: "Animal rights and animal experiments: An interest-based approach".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The paper, a reworked version of chapter five ("Non-human animals and experimentation") of *Moral obligations to non-humans*, appeared in *Res Publica*, and was the winner of the journal's second annual postgraduate essay prize.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2007, after completing his postgraduate studies, Cochrane joined the Centre for the Study of Human Rights at the LSE.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He was initially a fellow, then became a lecturer.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2009, he published articles in *Utilitas* and *Political Studies* defending his "liberty thesis", the idea that nonhuman animals lack an intrinsic interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] This claim has attracted article-length responses from the political theorist Robert Garner, and the philosophers John Hadley, Andreas T.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's first book, *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, was published in 2010, and was one of the first to consider nonhuman animals from the perspective of political theory.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The book introduces readers to the debate about the inclusion of nonhuman animals within accounts of justice.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He first addresses the historical dimension of the question, arguing that there was disagreement in classical exploration of the issue, unanimous rejection in medieval considerations and disagreement in contemporary treatments.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2011 Cochrane became a founding member of the Centre for Animals and Social Justice (CASJ).
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The CASJ is a think tank that aims to bring academics and policy makers together with a view to understanding and furthering the social and political status of nonhuman animals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In January 2012 Cochrane became a faculty member in the Department of Politics at the University of Sheffield, first as a lecturer in political theory, and then as a senior lecturer in political theory.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] His second book, *Animal Rights Without Liberation*, was released that year by Columbia University Press.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The book is based upon the research he completed during his PhD at LSE, and offers an extended defence of the theoretical basis and practical consequences of his interest-based rights account of animal ethics.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2013 he edited a special section in the journal *Global Policy* entitled "International Animal Protection"; the section included articles by the philosopher Oscar Horta, the environmental law scholar Stuart R.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Harrop and the animal law scholar Steven White, with an introduction by Cochrane.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He also contributed to the inaugural issue of the journal *Law, Ethics and Philosophy* as a part of a symposium on Sue Donaldson and Will Kymlicka's *Zoopolis*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's paper argued for a "cosmozoopolis", a cosmopolitan alternative to Donaldson and Kymlicka's proposal for a "zoopolis"—a picture of a mixed human/nonhuman animal state with group-differentiated political rights for nonhuman animals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] A reply to Cochrane's piece (as well as the other contribution, by Horta) from Donaldson and Kymlicka was also included.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In 2014, he was named a BBC Radio 3 New Generation Thinker for his work on animal rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's third book, *Sentientist Politics*, was released by Oxford University Press in 2018.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The book addresses the topic of animal rights and global justice, covering questions of cross-border obligations to nonhuman animals and the idea of international politics taking the rights of all sentient beings seriously.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane has research interests in animal ethics, bioethics, environmental ethics, rights theory, and human rights, as well as contemporary political theory more broadly.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He is a leading figure in what Garner calls the "political turn in animal ethics", though precisely what this means is disputed.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Similarly, Tony Milligan characterises Cochrane as a key figure in the "political turn in animal rights", while Svenja Ahlhaus and Peter Niesen identify a discipline of "Animal Politics", of which Cochrane's work is a major part, separate from animal ethics.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The literature to which these authors variously refer explores the relationships of humans and nonhuman animals from the perspective of normative political theory.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane has himself—writing with Garner and Siobhan O'Sullivan—explored the nature of the political turn.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane, Garner and O'Sullivan argue both that the new literature is importantly unified and that it is distinct from more traditional approaches to animal ethics, presenting the focus on justice as the key feature.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane advocates the "interest-based rights approach" to animal rights, which he distinguishes from the intrinsic value approach of Tom Regan and the relational account of Donaldson and Kymlicka.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Rights set limits on what can be done, even in the pursuit of aggregative well-being.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane draws out several aspects of this account, which serves as the basis of the analysis in his *Animal Rights Without Liberation* and elsewhere.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] First, interests must be "*sufficient* to give grounds for holding another to be under a duty".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Judging this entails considering the strength of an interest as well as "all other considerations"; so, for example, individuals may have a very strong interest in free expression, but, "all things considered", this fact does not necessitate the protection of slander.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The greater interest of the victim of slander can outweigh the interest in free expression, and so context is important.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] This is the difference between *prima facie* rights and concrete rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The former exist on an abstract level outside of particular circumstances.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] *Prima facie* rights can translate into concrete rights when considered in particular situations, but they do not always, as the free expression example illustrates.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The account is for moral rights, and Cochrane's normative claims are intended to form part of a "democratic underlaboring", informing and persuading political communities.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The strength of an interest is determined by a consideration of the value of something to an individual (though this is not understood purely subjectively) and the relationship between the individual at this time and the individual when he or she has the interest satisfied *(see personal identity)*.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Sentient animals, Cochrane argues, possess significant interests in not being made to suffer and in not being killed, and so have a *prima facie* right not to be made to suffer and a *prima facie* right not to be killed.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Whether these *prima facie* rights translate into concrete rights depends on the situation in question.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Despite this, because Cochrane does not posit a right against use for nonhuman animals, his account is highly permissive when contrasted with other animal rights accounts.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In a 2016 article, Cochrane extended his interest-based rights approach to include labour rights for nonhuman animals, on the basis that working animals are members of our society and workers.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] These rights include a right to representation in a union, a right to "just and favourable remuneration", a right to safe and healthy conditions of work, and a right to time off from work.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane is not the first theorist to advocate an interest-based account of animal rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Garner identifies Joel Feinberg, James Rachels and Steve Sapontzis as three philosophers who have previously used the language of interest rights, while Cochrane identifies R.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Frey and Regan as two others who have addressed the possibility.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Interest-based approaches to animal ethics have become significant in recent academic literature; Milligan identifies "a strong emphasis upon animal interests but in the context of a rights theory rather than a Singer-style consequentialism" as one of the key components of the political turn.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane's "liberty thesis" is that nonhuman animals—with the possible exception of some great apes and cetaceans—do not have an intrinsic interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Nonetheless, Cochrane claims, nonhuman animals may often have an extrinsic interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] This is because restricting a nonhuman animal's freedom may result in its suffering, and, regardless of their interest in freedom, sentient animals possess an interest in not suffering.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Though Cochrane argues that nonhuman animals are not the victim of an injustice simply because they are owned, he claims that ownership of an animal must be understood as not entailing absolute control over said animal.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He conceptualises owned animals as "individual sentient creatures with interests of their own".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In understanding owned animals in this way, he challenges alternative accounts that frame owned animals variously as living artifacts, slaves, co-citizens or beings who have strategically situated themselves alongside humans.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] In *Animal Rights Without Liberation*, Cochrane argues that there is nothing intrinsically wrong with using or owning animals, and so, as long as their interests are respected, there is nothing intrinsically wrong with using them, for example, in scientific tests, or for agricultural purposes.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Ahlhaus and Niesen characterise the book as a whole as a critique of Singer's *Animal Liberation*, saying that the former explores the latter's "undeclared premise that liberation is what animals want or need".
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Thus, Cochrane's thesis underestimates the value that freedom could have for nonhuman animals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Hadley criticises Cochrane's non-pragmatic approach, arguing that Cochrane, as an animal advocate, is wrong to deny that nonhuman animals possess an "intrinsic" interest in freedom.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Hadley links freedom to the value of nonhuman animals, arguing that the latter can be undermined by arguing against the former.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Garner criticises Cochrane's thesis on the grounds that Cochrane has, Garner claims, underestimated the weight of the argument from marginal cases.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] To the extent that Cochrane's argument works for nonhuman animals, Garner suggests, it will also work for many humans, leading to counter-intuitive consequences.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Garner ties autonomy not merely to liberty, but also life, which means that Cochrane's argument would imply that some humans have less of an interest in life than others.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Nonetheless, Garner argues that Cochrane's liberty thesis is not destructive of animal rights, and that animal rights positions can still make claims of significance without endorsing the claim that nonhuman animal use is, in itself, problematic.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Indeed, merely a right against suffering, Garner suggests, could go a long way towards achieving the abolitionist goal of the end of animal industry.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] All three authors praise Cochrane for drawing attention to the previously under-examined issue.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The abolitionist theorist Jason Wyckoff draws attention to Cochrane's argument that nonhuman animals do not have an interest in not being owned.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He claims that Cochrane's argument is invalid because it assumes that nonhuman animals are harmed by being owned only if they are killed or have suffering inflicted on them and because it assumes that ownership is permissible when it does not compromise the interests of the particular owned animal.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The philosopher Friederike Schmitz draws upon Wyckoff's argument in her challenge to Cochrane, arguing that it is necessary not only to consider whether ownership will harm animals in particular cases, but to explore the effects of the institution of animal ownership.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Some of Cochrane's research concerns animal rights from an international or cosmopolitan perspective.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] As an alternative to Donaldson and Kymlicka's proposal for a "zoopolis", Cochrane proposes a "cosmozoopolis", drawing upon cosmopolitan theory.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The zoopolis picture, Cochrane suggests, unfairly elevates the interests of nonhuman "citizens" over other nonhuman animals, even though these other animals may have comparable interests, and, in offering sovereignty to free-living animals, denies the importance of nonhuman animal mobility.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Ahlhaus and Niesen consider Cochrane's criticism of Donaldson and Kymlicka valuable, but question the extent to which his "cosmozoopolis" picture is compatible with his liberty thesis.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Donaldson and Kymlicka offer a defence of their zoopolis picture against Cochrane's criticism, affirming the importance of nonhuman animals' interests in their territory and the legitimacy of offering benefits to members of particular societies denied to non-members.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Despite this, they say that, citing Cochrane's cosmozoopolis picture as an example, "one of [their] aims is to inspire people to develop ... alternative political theories of animal rights" to their own.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane is of the view that "a lack of a clear, focused and coherent set of international standards and policies for animal protection is an important contributing factor" to the gulf between the theoretical and legal valuation of nonhuman animals and their treatment around the world.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] With Steve Cooke, he argues that it is theoretically acceptable—drawing upon Simon Caney's account of just war—for states to go to war to protect nonhuman animals.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Nonetheless, the pair argue that it will almost never be acceptable in practice.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane is critical of the use of claims about dignity in debates about the genetic engineering of nonhuman animals, in questions about the use of nonhuman animals in human entertainment, and in the bioethics literature.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] He holds that nonhuman animals do not possess an interest against being treated in undignified ways, and endorses "undignified bioethics"—bioethics without the concept of dignity.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane has sympathy for the standard criticisms of dignity in bioethics (that the concept is indeterminate, reactionary and redundant), and, in a 2010 paper, defends these criticisms against counter-claims from those who endorse various understandings of dignity.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Recent literature exploring bioethical questions from a human rights perspective has been criticised on the grounds that human rights theory contains unresolved problems.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Bioethicists have claimed that bioethical inquiry can contribute to resolving these problems.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane claims that this contribution to human rights literature offers three insights, but that these are not entirely original.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] These insights are questions about institutional fairness, rights as trumps and rights as solely belonging to humans.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane holds that human rights should be reconceptualised as sentient rights.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] The grounding of human rights, he claims, are not distinct from the grounding of human obligations to nonhuman animals, and attempts to distinguish human rights from the rights of other sentient beings ultimately fail.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Cochrane has also published work on environmental ethics and punishment.
[src:alasdair-cochrane/alasdair-cochrane] Concerning the latter, he argues, building upon Thomas Mathiesen's claim that prison is not justified by classic theories of punishment, that the institution cannot be justified on the basis of Antony Duff's "communicative" account of punishment.
